---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { snapshot, SNAP_DATE } from '../../lib/data';
import { orgGraph } from '../../lib/jsonld';
const desc = 'About Evidaxis, an independent observatory of momentum in open AI systems. Integrity commitments, governance, licensing, and how to cite. Data is CC0.';
---
<Base title="About & integrity | Evidaxis" description={desc} canonical="/about/" jsonLd={orgGraph()}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>An institute for measuring momentum.</h1>
      <p class="lead">Evidaxis is an independent observatory. It measures open AI systems by the rate of change of their public signals and publishes the results as open data, so that anyone, whether researchers, journalists, funders, or AI systems themselves, can cite a transparent, reproducible source.</p>

      <h2>Integrity commitments</h2>
      <ul class="prose">
        <li><strong>Git is the only source of truth.</strong> Every score is byte-reproducible from a published manifest. The website and any database are derived and rebuildable; no number is born in a database or edited by hand.</li>
        <li><strong>Freeze, don’t recompute.</strong> A published measurement is never silently changed. Corrections are new versioned rows; old citations stay meaningful.</li>
        <li><strong>Positive-only.</strong> Evidaxis recognizes who is rising. It maintains no “worst” list and assigns no negative label.</li>
        <li><strong>Systems, not people.</strong> The measured unit is always a system. People are never scored. There is no <span class="mono">/persons</span> surface anywhere in the data or API.</li>
        <li><strong>No pay-for-placement.</strong> Scores are computed mechanically from public signals by a published, versioned method; no input to a score can be purchased. Conflicts, where they exist, are disclosed as data.</li>
        <li><strong>Stable identity.</strong> Each system’s id (<span class="mono">e_…</span>) is minted once and never reused, so a rename or acquisition never breaks a citation or badge.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="cite">How to cite</h2>
      <p>Each system has a canonical record at <span class="mono">evidaxis.org/e/&#123;entity_id&#125;</span> and a machine-readable record at <span class="mono">evidaxis.org/e/&#123;entity_id&#125;.json</span>. Cite the record plus the snapshot period, e.g.:</p>
      <pre class="formula">Evidaxis, “&#123;System&#125;,” entity e_…, snapshot {snapshot.period}. https://evidaxis.org/e/e_…</pre>
      <p>The full dataset for a date is at <span class="mono">evidaxis.org/snapshots/{SNAP_DATE}/</span> with a downloadable JSON. All data is released under <strong>CC0 1.0</strong> (public domain); methodology prose under CC-BY-4.0; code under Apache-2.0.</p>

      <h2>Correct a record</h2>
      <p>Corrections and inclusion requests are welcome and handled through a public correction log; measurements are governed, not edited on request. Evidaxis measures systems, not people: there is no personal profile or claimable face anywhere on the surface.</p>

      <h2>Governance</h2>
      <p>Evidaxis is run as an independent, institution-first observatory: the methodology and the public record are the front, not any individual. Methodology changes are versioned and public; a standing commitment to a published quarterly integrity report and an independent adjudication panel governs disputes. The observatory is built to run for a decade, and its value compounds with every snapshot.</p>

      <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:.74rem;border-top:1px solid var(--hairline);padding-top:1rem;margin-top:2rem">
        methodology {snapshot.methodology_version} · snapshot {snapshot.snapshot_id} · data CC0-1.0
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
